# Reference template — the easiest way to create .env is:
#
#   bash setup.sh
#
# That script auto-detects the current directory and writes .env for you.
# If you prefer to set the path manually, copy this file to .env and edit:
#
#   cp .env.example .env
#
# ODIN_PIPELINE_ROOT must be the absolute WSL2/Linux path to the pipeline/
# subdirectory inside this repo (not the repo root itself).
# Windows example (WSL2): /mnt/c/ODIN/odin-demo/pipeline
# Linux / macOS example:  /home/user/odin-demo/pipeline

ODIN_PIPELINE_ROOT=/path/to/odin-demo/pipeline

# ── CORPORATE NETWORK / SSL INSPECTION ────────────────────────────────────────
# If your network intercepts HTTPS with a corporate CA certificate, place the
# cert (PEM format; single cert or multi-cert bundle both work) in the ca/
# folder — no env var needed. odin.config auto-discovers any *.cer/*.crt/*.pem
# file there at runtime and injects it into all pipeline containers.
# Only set ODIN_CA_CERT if your cert is stored outside the ca/ folder:
# ODIN_CA_CERT=/path/to/your/corporate-ca.cer

# ── RECOMMENDED ON WINDOWS/WSL2 ───────────────────────────────────────────────
# Set ODIN_WORK_DIR to a WSL2-native Linux path to avoid I/O failures when
# Nextflow task containers access work directories on a Windows filesystem.
# docker-compose.yml mounts this path identically (host:container) so that
# sibling pipeline containers can reach it via the Docker socket.
# Docker auto-creates the directory on first launch — no mkdir needed.
# Default when unset: /tmp/odin_work (also auto-created).
# ODIN_WORK_DIR=/home/<your-wsl-user>/odin_work

# ── OPTIONAL ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# ODIN_TMP_DIR=/var/tmp
# ODIN_LOG_DIR=/home/<your-wsl-user>/odin_logs
# ODIN_STORE_DIR=/home/<your-wsl-user>/odin_store
# TAXPROFILER_REVISION=1.2.6
# NEXTFLOW_CONFIG_FILE=/app/config/odin.config
# SQUIRREL_IMAGE=articnetworkorg/squirrel:1.3.2
